    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) is appropriate because it can incorporate the PDE, boundary, and initial conditions directly into the loss function without requiring discretized data. The network takes (x,t) as inputs and outputs u(x,t). The loss includes: (1) PDE residual: ∂u/∂t + v ∂u/∂x - D ∂²u/∂x², (2) boundary condition loss at domain edges, (3) initial condition loss at t=0. A fully connected feedforward network with tanh activation and 4-6 hidden layers of 50-100 neurons is a reasonable starting point. For advection-dominated regimes (high Péclet number), adaptive loss weighting or gradient clipping may be needed to avoid training instability. Alternatively, a Fourier feature embedding or a modified architecture (e.g., with periodic activations) can help capture high-frequency features.",
